        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Brit. Mus.</placeName>
                    <date>3<hi rend="superscript">rd</hi> April 1871</date>
                    <salute>My Dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I think I recollect having made a mistake in my letter to you yesterday.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I quoted “Isis” 1813 it ought to be 1831 &amp; Wagler thought it was the <hi rend="underline">female</hi> had the yellow dorsal spot.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Buffon called the male sloth L’ai adult. vol <hi rend="smallCaps">xiii</hi> to <hi rend="smallCaps">vi</hi> &amp; Daubenton too in his description calls it Ai de dos brulé vol <hi rend="smallCaps">xiii</hi> p 62.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> He says it has the appearance as if the hair of the back had been burnt</p>
<p>I have sent you on an American pamphlet I have received today<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Yours sincerely | J E Gray</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7652.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. E. Gray, 2 April 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Gray refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8021.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wagler 1831</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Gray refers to George Louis Leclerc, comte de Buffon, to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5493.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Louis-Jean-Marie Daubenton</ref>, and to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1052.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Buffon 1749–1804</ref>; for the ai adulte see vol. 13 plate vi.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">The pamphlet has not been identified.</note>
        </div>        
            
